m central to their lives. Opinion is thus a form of action as important as the mechanisms that organize votes and mobilize decisions. Urbinati focuses less on the overt enemies of democracy than on those who pose as its friends: technocrats wedded to procedure, demagogues who make glib appeals to "the people," and media operatives who, given their preference, would turn governance into a spectator sport and citizens into fans of opposing teams.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2014z9783110370416oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067472638340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674726383423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674726383.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-DSWb2014